    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm looking at this NDA my new contractor sent over and it's kind of a lot of legalese. can u just give me a quick summary of the main parts? like what exactly am i not allowed to share and how long does this thing last for? thanks.\n\n[Text of NDA:\nNON-DISCLOSURE AGREEMENT\nThis Non-Disclosure Agreement (the \"Agreement\") is entered into as of October 12, 2023, by and between Stellar Solutions LLC (\"Disclosing Party\") and Alex Rivera (\"Recipient\").\n1. Definition of Confidential Information. \"Confidential Information\" shall include all non-public, proprietary, or confidential information, whether oral or written, including but not limited to trade secrets, client lists, software code, and business strategies.\n2. Obligations of Recipient. Recipient agrees to hold all Confidential Information in strict confidence and shall not disclose such information to any third party without prior written consent.\n3. Term and Termination. This Agreement shall remain in effect for a period of three (3) years from the date of disclosure of the Confidential Information, notwithstanding the termination of the working relationship between the parties.\n4. Remedies. Recipient acknowledges that unauthorized disclosure may cause irreparable harm for which monetary damages may be inadequate, and Disclosing Party shall be entitled to seek injunctive relief.]",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The NDA between Stellar Solutions LLC and Alex Rivera (Recipient) restricts sharing any non-public, proprietary, or confidential information, which includes trade secrets, client lists, software code, and business strategies. The Recipient must keep this information confidential and can't disclose it without the Disclosing Party's consent. The agreement is valid for three years from the date the Confidential Information is shared, even if you end your working relationship with Stellar Solutions LLC. If someone breaks this rule, Stellar Solutions LLC can seek a court order to stop the breach (injunctive relief) because the damage may be too serious for just money.",
